{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17533658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17533658"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:37:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:37:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14856"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14856"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.65,0.01,0.02,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7547"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90492"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7547"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14856"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74739"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1731"},{"type":"tags","id":"3230"},{"type":"tags","id":"5820"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18465"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25046"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31033"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90492"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with painful neck spasms and difficulty speaking that began two hours ago. She has schizophrenia treated with haloperidol for the past year and epilepsy managed with sodium valproate. She experiences psychogenic non-epileptic seizures approximately monthly. She was prescribed metoclopramide yesterday for severe nausea. She has no other medical history and takes no other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. She has sustained contractions of her neck muscles affecting her speech. The remainder of the neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely precipitant of her acute dystonia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Haloperidol","Metoclopramide","Viral infection","Conversion disorder","Cervical disc prolapse"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with an acute dystonic reaction characterised by sustained muscle contractions affecting her neck and speech. While she is on \u003Cstrong\u003Ehaloperidol\u003C/strong\u003E, which she has been taking for the past year without incident, the temporal relationship strongly suggests that \u003Cstrong\u003Emetoclopramide\u003C/strong\u003E is the precipitant. Metoclopramide, a dopamine D2 receptor antagonist, commonly causes acute dystonic reactions, particularly in young adults and when combined with other dopamine-blocking agents like haloperidol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eviral infection\u003C/strong\u003E would not typically cause such rapid onset of focal dystonic symptoms. While viral illnesses can cause myalgia or meningismus, the pattern of involvement and temporal relationship to starting metoclopramide makes this unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDespite the patient\u0027s history of psychogenic non-epileptic seizures, a \u003Cstrong\u003Econversion disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to be the cause of these symptoms. While her background might make this diagnosis more plausible, the characteristic pattern of dystonia and clear temporal relationship to a medication known to cause this exact side effect makes conversion disorder less likely. Additionally, the presentation is typical for a medication-induced dystonia rather than the variable patterns typically seen in conversion disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical disc prolapse\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes radicular pain and neurological symptoms in a dermatomal distribution. The acute onset of dystonic posturing affecting multiple muscle groups would be unusual for a disc prolapse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management involves immediate administration of anticholinergic medication (such as benztropine) or antihistamines, discontinuation of metoclopramide, and consideration of an alternative antiemetic with less risk of extrapyramidal side effects. The presence of haloperidol likely increased her risk of developing an acute dystonic reaction when metoclopramide was added.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Metoclopramide commonly causes acute dystonic reactions, particularly in young adults.","Multiple dopamine-blocking agents increase the risk of acute dystonic reactions.","Recent medication changes are key to identifying the causative agent of acute dystonia.","The temporal relationship to medication changes is more significant than past medical history in diagnosing acute dystonia."],"references":["D\u0027Souza RS, Aslam SP, Hooten WM. Extrapyramidal Side Effects. [Updated 2025 Jan 19]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK534115/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74739"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14856"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74739"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T08:59:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-25T08:48:59+10:30"},"relationships"